Part 2 - Control Methods for 4x4 Frozen Lake¶

In Part 2, we will apply the dynamic programming control methods to find an optimal policy for the environment created in Part 1.

2.A - Policy Iteration¶

We will start by applying policy iteration. Complete the following instructions in the cell below.

  1. Create an instance of DPAgent for the environment from Part 1. Set the discount rate to 1, and set seed=1.
  2. Call the policy_iteration() method the agent using the default parameter values.
  3. Use the display_policy() method of the environment to display the optimal policy found by policy iteration.

Part 3 - 4x4 Frozen Lake with Time Step Penalty¶

The optimal policy found in Part 2 has a high success rate, but at the cost of very long episodes. This is because the agent has discovered that it can safely avoid most holes by trying to move directly away from them and hoping that it slips into one of the perpendicular directions instead. It is a clever strategy as long as the agent has no incentive to try to reach the goal quickly.

In Part 3, we will introduce a time step penalty that will prompt the agent to solve the task quickly while maintaining a reasonably high success rate.

3.A - Optimal Policy for Custom Environment¶

Complete the following steps in the cell below:

  1. Create a new instance of the Frozen Lake environment. This version should be identical to the version created in Step 1.A, except that the reward structure should be set to [-2, -10, 100].

  2. Create an instance of DPAgent for the environment wih a seed of 1 and discount factor of 1.0.

  3. Run value iteration with the default parameters.

  4. Use the evaluate() method to measure the performance of the agent. Use 1000 episodes and set seed=1, gamma=1.0, and check_sucess=True.

You should see that the optimal policy for this version of the environment has a success rate of approximately 0.744 and an average episode length of about 7.

Now, adjust the reward structure of the environment and re-run the code. Your goal is to find a reward structure that will result in an optiomal policy with a success rate of at least 0.84, and with a mean episode length less than 25. You should be able to accomplish this by changing only the first element of the reward structure (which is the time step penalty).

In [16]:
env2 = gym.make(name = 'FrozenLake-v1',prob = 0.8,rew_struct = [-.2, -10, 100],render_mode = 'rgb_array')

dp_agent4 = DPAgent(env2, gamma=1.0, seed=1)
dp_agent4.value_iteration()

evaluate(env2, dp_agent4, episodes = 1000, seed = 1, gamma = 1.0, check_success = True)

Part 4 - 32x32 Frozen Lake¶

We will now apply value iteration to a much larger version of the Frozen Lake environment.

4.A - Create and Display Environment¶

The cell below creates a 32x32 version of the Frozen Lake environment with a custom reward structure. Run this cell as is for now, but you will be asked to come back and adjust the reward structure in step 4.B.

In [20]:
env4 = gym.make(
    'FrozenLake-v1',
    prob = 0.9,
    rew_struct = [-.9, -10, 100],
    desc = generate_random_map(size=32, p=0.8, seed=8),
    max_episode_steps = 1000,
    render_mode = 'rgb_array'
)

obs, info = env4.reset()
plt.figure(figsize=[6,6])
plt.imshow(env4.render())
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()
